05101nam a22007575i 9780228009597DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280095977 a10.1515/97802280095972doi  a(DE-B1597)656676  a(OCoLC)1394873228  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBL2566.P9bI33 2021 7aSOC0080502bisacsh04a200.972952231 aIgartua, José E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommunities of the Soul :bA Short History of Religion in Puerto Rico /cJosé E. Igartua. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b12 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v9000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tLife and Religion among the Taíno -- tThe Catholic Church in Spain, 16th–18th Centuries -- tThe Catholic Church in Puerto Rico, 16th–18th Centuries -- tReligious Counter-Revolution in Puerto Rico, 19th Century -- tChallenges to Orthodoxy, 1870–1900 -- tAmerican Dominion, 1898–1930 -- tProtestantism, 1898–1960 -- tThe Catholic Church and the State, 1930–70 -- tVarieties of Monotheism: Protestants, Jews, and Muslims in the Late 20th Century -- tNon-Institutional Forms of Religious Practice in the Late 20th Century -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion is fundamental to contemporary Puerto Rican society. From the cosmology of the Indigenous Taíno, to the wide range of Judeo-Christian churches and sects, to the practitioners of spiritism, Afro-Caribbean religions, and witchcraft, religious practice in its many forms permeates the lives of most Puerto Ricans.Communities of the Soul illuminates the landscape and history of religion in Puerto Rico from the beliefs and practices of the Taíno to the religious diversity of the present day. Throughout its history, religion in Puerto Rico has braided institutional forms and popular practices, yet has always been a community-based process – made by the people. When the island was under Spanish colonial rule, the formal but weak presence of Catholicism meant that Puerto Ricans cultivated their religious experiences within families and local communities as much as within the structures of the church. These communal practices continued as Puerto Ricans joined Protestant denominations – particularly evangelical Pentecostalism – after the American conquest of the island in 1898. In the second half of the twentieth century, religious diversity increased with the formation of Jewish and Muslim communities, as well as numerous local evangelical congregations. Even as Puerto Rican society becomes more cosmopolitan and diverse, popular devotions and ritualistic practices remain an important part of everyday life.The first synthesis of the religious history of the island, Communities of the Soul is an innovative exploration of religion in Puerto Rico and the beliefs, practices, and diversity of its past and present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Caribbean & Latin American Studies.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aCheos.  aFreemasonry.  aIslam.  aJudaism.  aMarian devotion.  aMuslim.  aPentecostalism.  aProtestantism.  aTaino.  abrotherhoods.  aclergy.  afaith healing.  alay preachers.  aliberation theology.  amissionaries.  apractice.  asanteria.  aspiritism.  awitchcraft.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Packag